Aire and Calder Navigation.label: Aire and Calder Navigation
Aire and Calder Navigation.description: The Aire and Calder Navigation is a river and canal system of the River Aire and the River Calder in the metropolitan county of West Yorkshire, England. Wikipedia

Bridgwater and Taunton Canal.label: Bridgwater and Taunton Canal
Bridgwater and Taunton Canal.description: The Bridgwater and Taunton Canal is a canal in the south-west of England between Bridgwater and Taunton, opened in 1827 and linking the River Tone to the River Parrett. Wikipedia

Erie Canal.label: Erie Canal
Erie Canal.description: The Erie Canal is a canal in New York that originally ran about 363 miles from Albany, New York, on the Hudson River to Buffalo, New York, at Lake Erie. Wikipedia

Foss Dyke.label: Foss Dyke
Foss Dyke.description: The Foss Dyke, or Fossdyke, connects the River Trent at Torksey to Lincoln, the county town of Lincolnshire, and may be the oldest canal in England that is still in use. Wikipedia

Haddiscoe Cut.label: Haddiscoe Cut
Haddiscoe Cut.description: The Haddiscoe Cut or New Cut is a canal in the English county of Norfolk and in The Broads National Park. Wikipedia

Herefordshire and Gloucestershire Canal.label: Herefordshire and Gloucestershire Canal
Herefordshire and Gloucestershire Canal.description: The Herefordshire and Gloucestershire Canal is a canal in the west of England, which ran from Hereford to Gloucester, where it linked to the River Severn. Wikipedia

Huddersfield Narrow Canal.label: Huddersfield Narrow Canal
Huddersfield Narrow Canal.description: The Huddersfield Narrow Canal is an inland waterway in Northern England. It runs just under 20 miles from Lock 1E at the rear of the University of Huddersfield campus, near Aspley Basin at Huddersfield ... Wikipedia

Lancaster Canal.label: Lancaster Canal
Lancaster Canal.description: The Lancaster Canal is a canal in the north of England, originally planned to run from Westhoughton in Lancashire to Kendal in south Cumbria. Wikipedia

Manchester Ship Canal.label: Manchester Ship Canal
Manchester Ship Canal.description: The Manchester Ship Canal is an inland waterway 36 miles long in the North West of England. Starting at the Mersey Estuary near Liverpool, it generally follows the original routes of the rivers Mersey ... Wikipedia

River Gipping.label: River Gipping
River Gipping.description: The River Gipping is the source river for the River Orwell in the county of Suffolk in East Anglia, England, which gave its name to the former Gipping Rural District and the village of Gipping. Wikipedia

Saint Lawrence Seaway.label: Saint Lawrence Seaway
Saint Lawrence Seaway.description: The Saint Lawrence Seaway is the common name for a system of locks, canals and channels that permits ocean-going vessels to travel from the Atlantic Ocean to the Great Lakes, as far inland as the western end of Lake Superior. Wikipedia

Stratford-upon-Avon Canal.label: Stratford-upon-Avon Canal
Stratford-upon-Avon Canal.description: The Stratford-upon-Avon Canal is a canal in the south Midlands of England. The canal, which was built between 1793 and 1816, runs for 25.5 miles in total, and consists of two sections. Wikipedia

Thames and Severn Canal.label: Thames and Severn Canal
Thames and Severn Canal.description: The Thames and Severn Canal is a canal in Gloucestershire in the south of England, which was completed in 1789. It was conceived as part of a canal route from Bristol to London. Wikipedia

Trent and Mersey Canal.label: Trent and Mersey Canal
Trent and Mersey Canal.description: The Trent and Mersey Canal is a 93.5-mile long canal in the East Midlands, West Midlands, and north-west of England. Wikipedia

Windawski Canal.label: Windawski Canal
Windawski Canal.description: The Windawski Canal is an abandoned canal connecting the Dubysa River near Bazilionai, Šiauliai district to the Venta River near Tolučiai Šaukėnų, Kelmė District of Lithuania. Wikipedia

Suez Canal.label: Suez Canal
Suez Canal.description: The Suez Canal is an artificial sea-level waterway in Egypt, connecting the Mediterranean Sea and the Red Sea. Wikipedia

Braunton Canal.label: Braunton Canal
Braunton Canal.description: The Braunton Canal is a cut made to straighten the course of the upper section of the River Caen, known as Braunton Pill, and to provide a new quay for the village of Braunton in North Devon, England. Wikipedia

Sandy and Beaver Canal.label: Sandy and Beaver Canal
Sandy and Beaver Canal.description: The Sandy and Beaver Canal ran 73 miles from the Ohio and Erie Canal at Bolivar, Ohio, to the Ohio River at Glasgow, Pennsylvania. It had 90 locks, was chartered in 1828 and completed in 1848. Wikipedia

River Humber.label: Humber
River Humber.description: The Humber is a large tidal estuary on the east coast of Northern England. It is formed at Trent Falls, Faxfleet, by the confluence of the tidal rivers Ouse and Trent. Wikipedia

Bentley Canal.label: Bentley Canal
Bentley Canal.description: The Bentley Canal is an abandoned canal that was part of the Birmingham Canal Navigations. A very short section still exists where it joins the Wyrley and Essington Canal in Wolverhampton. Wikipedia

Chard Canal.label: Chard Canal
Chard Canal.description: The Chard Canal was a 13.5 miles tub boat canal in Somerset, England, that ran from the Bridgwater and Taunton Canal at Creech St. Michael, over four aqueducts, through three tunnels and four inclined planes to Chard. Wikipedia

Fradley Junction.label: Fradley Junction
Fradley Junction.description: Fradley Junction is a canal junction between Fradley and Alrewas near Lichfield, Staffordshire, England and the point at which the Coventry Canal joins the Trent and Mersey Canal. Wikipedia

Grantham Canal.label: Grantham Canal
Grantham Canal.description: The Grantham Canal is a canal that runs for 33 miles from Grantham, falling through 18 locks to West Bridgford where it joins the River Trent. It was built primarily to allow for the transportation of coal to Grantham. Wikipedia

Hertford Union Canal.label: Hertford Union Canal
Hertford Union Canal.description: The Hertford Union Canal or Duckett's Canal is a short stretch of canal in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets in East London. It connects the Regent's Canal to the Lee Navigation. It was opened in 1830 but quickly proved to be a commercial failure. Wikipedia

Peak Forest Canal.label: Peak Forest Canal
Peak Forest Canal.description: The Peak Forest Canal is a narrow locked artificial waterway in northern England. It is 14.8 miles long and forms part of the connected English/Welsh inland waterway network. Wikipedia

Rochdale Canal.label: Rochdale Canal
Rochdale Canal.description: The Rochdale Canal is a navigable broad canal in Northern England, between Manchester and Sowerby Bridge, part of the connected system of the canals of Great Britain. Wikipedia

Stockport Branch Canal.label: Stockport Branch Canal
Stockport Branch Canal.description: The Stockport Branch Canal was a 5 mile branch of the Ashton Canal from Clayton to Stockport Wikipedia

Adelphi Canal.label: Adelphi Canal
Adelphi Canal.description: The Adelphi Canal was a small privately owned canal in Duckmanton, near Chesterfield, England. It was used to transport goods from an ironworks to a wharf by the road. Wikipedia

Bridgewater Canal.label: Bridgewater Canal
Bridgewater Canal.description: The Bridgewater Canal connects Runcorn, Manchester and Leigh, in North West England. It was commissioned by Francis Egerton, 3rd Duke of Bridgewater, to transport coal from his mines in Worsley to Manchester. Wikipedia

Chesterfield Canal.label: Chesterfield Canal
Chesterfield Canal.description: The Chesterfield Canal is in the north of England and it is known locally as 'Cuckoo Dyke'. It was opened in 1777 and ran 46 miles from the River Trent at West Stockwith, Nottinghamshire to Chesterfield, Derbyshire. Wikipedia

Cromford Canal.label: Cromford Canal
Cromford Canal.description: The Cromford Canal ran 14.5 miles from Cromford to the Erewash Canal in Derbyshire, England with a branch to Pinxton. Built by William Jessop with the assistance of Benjamin Outram, its alignment included four tunnels and 14 locks. Wikipedia

Erewash Canal.label: Erewash Canal
Erewash Canal.description: The Erewash Canal is a broad canal in Derbyshire, England. It runs just under 12 miles and has 14 locks. The first lock at Langley Bridge is actually part of the Cromford Canal. Wikipedia

Nottingham Canal.label: Nottingham Canal
Nottingham Canal.description: The Nottingham Canal was a 23.6 kilometres long canal between Langley Mill in Derbyshire and Nottingham, England. It opened in 1796, and most of it was closed in 1937. Wikipedia

Leeds & Liverpool Canal.label: Leeds and Liverpool Canal
Leeds & Liverpool Canal.description: The Leeds and Liverpool Canal is a canal in Northern England, linking the cities of Leeds and Liverpool. Over a distance of 127 miles, it crosses the Pennines, and includes 91 locks on the main line. Wikipedia

Baybridge Canal.label: Baybridge Canal
Baybridge Canal.description: The Baybridge Canal was a short canal built entirely within the parish of West Grinstead in the English county of Sussex. It opened in 1826, and closed in 1875. Wikipedia

Bradford Canal.label: Bradford Canal
Bradford Canal.description: The Bradford Canal was a 3.5-mile English canal which ran from the Leeds and Liverpool Canal at Shipley into the centre of Bradford. It opened in 1774, and was closed in 1866, when it was declared to be a public health hazard. Wikipedia

City Road Basin.label: City Road Basin
City Road Basin.description: The City Road Basin is an English canal basin and part of the Regent's Canal in London, owned by British Waterways. It opened in 1820, and made a large contributuion to the prosperity of the Regent's Canal. Wikipedia

Horncastle Canal.label: Horncastle Canal
Horncastle Canal.description: The Horncastle Canal was a broad canal which ran 11 miles from the River Witham to Horncastle in Lincolnshire, England, through twelve locks largely following the course of River Bain. Wikipedia

Industrial Canal.label: Industrial Canal
Industrial Canal.description: The Industrial Canal is a 5.5 mile waterway in New Orleans, Louisiana, United States. The waterway's proper name, as used by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and on NOAA nautical charts, is Inner Harbor Navigation Canal. Wikipedia

Leven Canal.label: Leven Canal
Leven Canal.description: The Leven Canal runs for 3.25 miles from the River Hull to the village of Leven, East Riding of Yorkshire, England. It was built for Mrs Charlotta Bethell in 1805, and remained in use until 1935. It is now a Site of Special Scientific Interest. Wikipedia

Neath and Tennant Canal.label: Neath and Tennant Canal
Neath and Tennant Canal.description: The Neath and Tennant Canals are two independent but linked canals in South Wales that are usually regarded as a single canal. Wikipedia

Sheffield Canal.label: Sheffield Canal
Sheffield Canal.description: The Sheffield Canal is a canal in the City of Sheffield, England. It runs 3.9 miles from Tinsley, where it leaves the River Don, to the Sheffield Canal Basin in the city centre, passing through 11 locks. Wikipedia

Stover Canal.label: Stover Canal
Stover Canal.description: The Stover Canal is a canal located in Devon, England. It was opened in 1792 and served the ball clay industry until it closed in the early 1940s. Wikipedia

Yorkshire Ring.label: Yorkshire Ring
Yorkshire Ring.description: The Yorkshire Ring is a canal ring in South and West Yorkshire, England. It was completed in 1905 with the construction of the New Junction Canal. Wikipedia

Regent's Canal.label: Regent's Canal
Regent's Canal.description: Regent's Canal is a canal across an area just north of central London, England. It provides a link from the Paddington arm of the Grand Union Canal, just north-west of Paddington Basin in the west, to ... Wikipedia

Welland Canal.label: Welland Canal
Welland Canal.description: The Welland Canal is a ship canal in Ontario, Canada, connecting Lake Ontario and Lake Erie. Traversing the Niagara Peninsula from Port Weller to Port Colborne, the canal forms a key section of the St. ... Wikipedia

Spon Lane Locks Branch.label: Spon Lane Locks Branch
Spon Lane Locks Branch.description: The Spon Lane Locks Branch is an 800-yard section of the BCN Main Line canal in Oldbury, England, which forms a connecting canal "sliproad" where the Old BCN Main Line crosses the New BCN Main Line at the Stewart Aqueduct. Wikipedia

Caledonian Canal.label: Caledonian Canal
Caledonian Canal.description: The Caledonian Canal is a canal in Scotland that connects the Scottish east coast at Inverness with the west coast at Corpach near Fort William. Wikipedia

Ligovsky Canal.label: Ligovsky Canal
Ligovsky Canal.description: Ligovsky Canal is one of the most extended channels of Saint Petersburg. It has been constructed in 1721, its length has made 23 kilometres. The channel was under construction for functioning of fountains of Summer garden. Wikipedia

Union Canal (Pennsylvania).label: Union Canal
Union Canal (Pennsylvania).description: The Union Canal was a towpath canal that existed in southeastern Pennsylvania in the United States during the 19th century. Wikipedia

Chemung Canal.label: Chemung Canal
Chemung Canal.description: The Chemung Canal is a former canal in New York, USA. The canal connected Seneca Lake at Watkins Glen to the Chemung River at Elmira, New York. Wikipedia

Augustów Canal.label: Augustów Canal
Augustów Canal.description: The Augustów Canal is a cross-border canal built in the 19th century in the present-day Podlaskie Voivodeship of northeastern Poland and the Grodno Region of north-western Belarus. Wikipedia

Panama Canal.label: Panama Canal
Panama Canal.description: The Panama Canal is a 77.1-kilometre ship canal in Panama that connects the Atlantic Ocean to the Pacific Ocean. The canal cuts across the Isthmus of Panama and is a key conduit for international maritime trade. Wikipedia

Aike Beck.label: Aike Beck
Aike Beck.description: Aike Beck or the Lockington Navigation is a stream in the East Riding of Yorkshire, England, which was constructed as a navigation in the late 18th century, and ceased to function as such in the 1850s. Wikipedia

Duluth Ship Canal.label: Duluth Ship Canal
Duluth Ship Canal.description: The Duluth Ship Canal is an artificial channel cut through Minnesota Point, providing direct access to Duluth harbor from Lake Superior. Begun privately in 1871, it was put under federal supervision and maintenance several years later. Wikipedia

Ganges Canal (Rajasthan).label: Ganges Canal
Ganges Canal (Rajasthan).description: The Ganges or Ganga Canal of Rajasthan is an irrigation system of canals laid down by Maharaja Ganga Singh of Bikaner in his Princely state in the early Nineteenth century in today's district of Sri Ganganagar. Wikipedia

Hardings Wood Junction.label: Hardings Wood Junction
Hardings Wood Junction.description: Hardings Wood Junction is a canal junction near Kidsgrove, Staffordshire, England and the point at which the Macclesfield Canal joins the Trent and Mersey Canal. It opened in 1831. Wikipedia

Manchester and Salford Junction Canal.label: Manchester and Salford Junction Canal
Manchester and Salford Junction Canal.description: The Manchester and Salford Junction Canal was a canal in the city of Manchester. It was originally built to provide a direct waterway between the Mersey and Irwell Navigation and the Rochdale Canal. Wikipedia

Andover Canal.label: Andover Canal
Andover Canal.description: The Andover Canal was a canal built in Hampshire, England. It ran 22 miles from Andover to Redbridge through Stockbridge and Romsey. Wikipedia

Ashby Canal.label: Ashby Canal
Ashby Canal.description: The Ashby-de-la-Zouch Canal is a 31-mile long canal in England which connected the mining district around Moira, just outside the town of Ashby-de-la-Zouch, with the Coventry Canal at Bedworth in Warwickshire. Wikipedia

Ashton Canal.label: Ashton Canal
Ashton Canal.description: The Ashton Canal is a canal in Greater Manchester in North West England. Wikipedia

Onega Canal.label: Onega Canal
Onega Canal.description: The Onega Canal is a canal that runs along the southern banks of Lake Onega in Vytegorsky District of Vologda Oblast and Podporozhsky District of Leningrad Oblasts in Russia. Wikipedia

Basingstoke Canal.label: Basingstoke Canal
Basingstoke Canal.description: The Basingstoke Canal is a British canal, completed in 1794, built to connect Basingstoke with the River Thames at Weybridge via the Wey Navigation. Wikipedia

Soho Loop.label: Soho Loop
Soho Loop.description: The Soho Loop is a 1.2-mile section of the eighteenth-century Old BCN Main Line canal in Birmingham, England, about 1.2 miles west of the city centre, which opened to traffic on 6 November 1769, and ... Wikipedia

Birmingham and Fazeley Canal.label: Birmingham and Fazeley Canal
Birmingham and Fazeley Canal.description: The Birmingham and Fazeley Canal is a canal of the Birmingham Canal Navigations in the West Midlands of England. Wikipedia

Bow Back Rivers.label: Bow Back Rivers
Bow Back Rivers.description: Bow Back Rivers or Stratford Back Rivers is a complex of waterways between Bow and Stratford in east London, England, which connect the River Lea to the River Thames. Wikipedia

Chichester Canal.label: Chichester Canal
Chichester Canal.description: The Chichester Canal is a navigable canal in England. It runs 4.5 miles from the sea at Birdham Chichester Harbour to Chichester through two locks. The canal was opened in 1822 having taken three years to build. Wikipedia

Montgomery Canal.label: Montgomery Canal
Montgomery Canal.description: The Montgomery Canal, or Montgomeryshire Canal, known colloquially as "The Monty", is a partially restored canal in Powys, in eastern Wales, and in northwest Shropshire, in western England. Wikipedia

Sheffield and South Yorkshire Navigation.label: Sheffield and South Yorkshire Navigation
Sheffield and South Yorkshire Navigation.description:
The Sheffield and South Yorkshire Navigation is a system of navigable inland waterways in South Yorkshire and Lincolnshire, England.
Chiefly based on the River Don, it runs for a length of 43 miles and has 27 locks. Wikipedia

Staffordshire and Worcestershire Canal.label: Staffordshire and Worcestershire Canal
Staffordshire and Worcestershire Canal.description: The Staffordshire and Worcestershire Canal is a navigable narrow canal in Staffordshire and Worcestershire in the English Midlands. Wikipedia

Strabane Canal.label: Strabane Canal
Strabane Canal.description: The Strabane Canal is a short canal in County Tyrone, Northern Ireland. It connected the market town of Strabane to the navigable River Foyle and thence to the port of Londonderry on the north coast of Ireland. Wikipedia

Wilts & Berks Canal.label: Wilts & Berks Canal
Wilts & Berks Canal.description: The Wilts & Berks Canal is a canal in the historic counties of Wiltshire and Berkshire, England, linking the Kennet and Avon Canal at Semington, near Melksham, to the River Thames at Abingdon. Wikipedia

Codorus Navigation.label: Codorus Navigation
Codorus Navigation.description: The Codorus Navigation Company, based in York in south-central Pennsylvania, was formed in 1829 to make a navigable waterway along Codorus Creek from York to the Susquehanna River, a distance of 11 miles. Wikipedia

Dingwall Canal.label: Dingwall Canal
Dingwall Canal.description: The Dingwall Canal was a short tidal canal running from the town of Dingwall to the Cromarty Firth in the county of Ross and Cromarty, Scotland. Wikipedia

Forth and Cart Canal.label: Forth and Cart Canal
Forth and Cart Canal.description: The Forth and Cart Canal was a short 0.5-mile link canal which provided a short cut between the Forth and Clyde Canal, at Whitecrook, and the River Clyde, opposite the mouth of the River Cart. Wikipedia

Four Counties Ring.label: Four Counties Ring
Four Counties Ring.description: The Four Counties Ring is a canal ring which links the English counties of Cheshire, Staffordshire, Shropshire and the West Midlands. Wikipedia

Kidwelly and Llanelly Canal.label: Kidwelly and Llanelly Canal
Kidwelly and Llanelly Canal.description: The Kidwelly and Llanelly Canal was a canal and tramroad system in Carmarthenshire, Wales, built to carry anthracite coal to the coast for onward transportation by coastal ships. Wikipedia

Pensnett Canal.label: Pensnett Canal
Pensnett Canal.description: The Pensnett Canal, also called Lord Ward's Canal was a private 1.25 miles long canal near Brierley Hill, West Midlands, England. The engineer was Mathew Frost. It has now almost entirely been lost by overbuilding. Wikipedia

Runcorn and Weston Canal.label: Runcorn and Weston Canal
Runcorn and Weston Canal.description: The Runcorn and Weston Canal was a short canal near Runcorn in Cheshire, England, constructed to link the Weston Canal, which is part of the River Weaver Navigation, to the Bridgewater Canal and Runcorn Docks. Wikipedia

Winter Canal.label: Winter Canal
Winter Canal.description:
Winter Canal is a canal in Saint Petersburg, Russia, connecting Bolshaya Neva with Moika River in the vicinity of Winter Palace.
The canal was dug in 1718–1719. Its length is only 228 metres, which makes it one of the shortest canals in the city. Wikipedia

Wisbech Canal.label: Wisbech Canal
Wisbech Canal.description: The Wisbech Canal was a broad canal near Wisbech in the Fenland area of Cambridgeshire, England. It ran from the River Nene at Wisbech to the Well Creek at Outwell in Norfolk, which gave access to the River Great Ouse. Wikipedia

Enfield Falls Canal.label: Enfield Falls Canal
Enfield Falls Canal.description: Enfield Falls Canal is a canal that was built to circumvent the shallows at Enfield Falls on the Connecticut River, en route either to or from Springfield, Massachusetts. Wikipedia

Haulover Canal.label: Haulover Canal
Haulover Canal.description: The Haulover Canal is a waterway north of Merritt Island, Florida, near the former site of Allenhurst, that connects Mosquito Lagoon with the Indian River, and is part of the Intracoastal Waterway. Wikipedia

Jonglei Canal.label: Jonglei Canal
Jonglei Canal.description: The Jonglei Canal is a project that has been proposed, started but never completed to divert water through the vast Sudd wetlands of South Sudan so as to deliver more water downstream to Sudan and Egypt for use in agriculture. Wikipedia

Lachine Canal.label: Lachine Canal
Lachine Canal.description: The Lachine Canal is a canal passing through the southwestern part of the Island of Montreal, Quebec, Canada, running 14.5 kilometres from the Old Port of Montreal to Lake Saint-Louis, through the boroughs of Lachine, Lasalle and Sud-Ouest. Wikipedia

Rochdale Branch Canal.label: Rochdale Branch Canal
Rochdale Branch Canal.description: The Rochdale Branch Canal was a branch of the Rochdale Canal in north-west England which led close to Rochdale Town Centre. It was in use from 1794, and was bordered by the landscaped gardens of Lark Mill House on the western bank until the 1850s. Wikipedia

Denison Canal.label: Denison Canal
Denison Canal.description: The Denison Canal is a man made canal located at Dunalley in southern Tasmania which opened for use in 1905 and gets its name from former Governor William Denison. Wikipedia
